Comment: The beginnings of Reti.
I gave him an easy pawn.  A truly dumb mistake on my part.  While it opens up the board, it's not what I wanted to do.
At this point, Dad said, "Thanks!"

Down a pawn, my tack is going to be conservative.  Might as well pressure his knight and open up the board.  I could have pressured with the queen, but didn't want to block up the avenues for developing other pieces.  I certainly didn't want to offer a trade by moving Nc6.

According to the book ...
1. Nf3 e5 2. Nxe5 d6 3. Nf3
A04: Reti opening
A bit aggressive all things considered, but it does present some options down the road.
Dad's been playing the c-pawn early a lot lately.  I seem to see this a lot lately, and I've started doing so myself as white.
I'm not sure why I'm not developing my king side at this point.  I suppose I'm trying to build support for an eventual pawn move to c5.
Dad has a strong center pawn structure now.
This seems like a mistake as it blocks the kingside development even further.
Dad strengthens the middle more.
This move was not necessary.  It only speeds up the game.  With a pawn down, this probably wasn't wise.  The only advantage it confers is a stacked pawn structure.
I'm not sure I would have exposed the King here, but he did.
Simple harassment without meaningful development.
A simple block that also develops the queenside.
I'm looking ahead to the possibility of Nf5 thus pressuring the bishop blocking the queen check.
Massive knight fork possibility at Nxc7 .

Argh, pesky knights.  Obviously, a6 leads to a fork.  O-O-O loses a pawn.  Rc8 loses a pawn.  I think Kd8 is the only move that I have here. Thoughts?  By moving the king, I've given up the ability to castle either way.
With the king out of position, it makes sense to pressure that side of the board.
A simple defensive move.
